      SPM Batch Editor.<p>

      AFFICHER PLUTOT UNE IMAGE QUI VAUT MILLE MOTS
      A typical dataset for an fmri study should look like this<p>
            study-->subjects1-->anatomicals    ->some dicom files<br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;|<PRE>         </PRE>|-->gre_field_map<PRE> </PRE>->some dicom files<br>
                 |           |-->fmri_session1 ->some dicom files<br>
                 |           |-->fmri_session2 ->some dicom file<br>
                 |           |   ...
                 |           |-->onset_for_fmri.m <em>(optionnal)</em>
                 |           ...<br>
                 |<br>
                 |-->subjects2-->anatomicals<br>
                 |           |-->gre_field_map ->some dicom files<br>
                 |           |-->fmri_session1 ->some dicom files<br>
                 |           |-->fmri_session2 ->some dicom file<br>
                 |           |   ... 
                 |           |-->onset_for_fmri.m <em>(optionnal)</em>
                 |           |...<br>
                 |--> ...<br>
                 | ...<br><br>


      Note: the name of anatomical and fmri directories between eachs subjects<br>
      involved in the analysis should all have at least the same name and most<br>
      of the time the same number of files inside<p>

      SPM Batch pipeline will:<br>
      1- Convert DICOM images into something SPM can use. (Two file (hdr+img) NIfTI)<br>
      2- Create field maps and unwarping EPI if requested.<br>
      3- Run from first to last a given matlab file list create by the tools SPM8 Batch Editor<br>
         Note, Batch must have been save in text format (Matlab .m Script File)
      
